<p>Seasonal variations in Kansas provide interesting solar production patterns. Summer months deliver peak production, with systems generating 20-30% more electricity than the annual average. However, even winter months maintain respectable production levels, often exceeding 70% of summer output due to the state's clear winter skies and the improved efficiency of solar panels in cooler temperatures. This consistent year-round production helps offset seasonal energy usage patterns and provides reliable electricity generation regardless of the season.</p>

