  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">What SEER rating is recommended for Kansas?</h3>
    <p>For Kansas's climate, HVAC systems with SEER ratings of 16 or higher are recommended to balance efficiency with cost-effectiveness. While the federal minimum SEER requirement is 14, Kansas homeowners benefit significantly from higher-efficiency units due to the state's hot, humid summers and extended cooling seasons. Systems with SEER ratings of 18-20 provide excellent efficiency for those seeking maximum energy savings, while SEER 16 units offer good efficiency at more moderate price points. Heat pumps with HSPF ratings of 8.5 or higher are recommended for year-round comfort and efficiency.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Does Kansas have net metering for solar panels?</h3>
    <p>Yes, Kansas maintains net metering policies that allow solar panel owners to receive credit for excess electricity generated by their systems. Evergy and most other Kansas utilities offer net metering programs that credit solar customers at retail rates for surplus electricity fed back into the grid. These credits can be used to offset electricity consumption during periods when solar panels aren't producing enough to meet household demand, such as nighttime or cloudy days. Net metering makes solar installations more economically attractive by maximizing the value of solar electricity production throughout the year.</p>`;
